  ('3778375d-6c06-42b1-8228-6e0d7f393151', 'WA AI COP Supplement', 'Julia Bloom-Weltman', current_timestamp(),
   'Okay to Proceed', 'Grant', 'Priority states and regions demonstrate increased human, technical, governance, and data infrastructure capacity to responsibly test, evaluate, procure and adopt AI-enabled data solutions aligned to student needs, system goals, and guardrails for safety, privacy and equity.',
   'sfl', 'sfl-bow2', NULL,
   'ASU Foundation', 200000, 200000,
   'Original investment co-funded with WSI', 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '1 year',
   'As we continue to reflect and evaluate the progress and engagement of Phase 1, we are seeing a lot of momentum and a high level of readiness across districts to implement the pilot projects they are developing. We see this as a unique opportunity to scale the impact/learning of this investment both in WA and across the national portfolio. We propose expanding the budget to allow three additional districts to be part of Phase 2, which would expand our total cohort to six districts.

To ensure we maintain the high quality of our community of practice and properly support a larger cohort, we would need to scale up our technical assistance, coaching, and project management resources. We have put together a preliminary budget if we were to go this route:

Proposed Additional Budget & Support:
•	$135,000 – District Grants: This adds 3 additional districts at $45,000 each, bringing us to a total of 6 fully supported districts. (If districts choose to ask for less than $45k, there is a chance we could accept additional teams or reduce this dollar amount)
•	$25,000 – CRPE: To support the expanded research/learning agenda and progress monitoring 
•	$25,000 – Education First: For additional 1:1 district coaching capacity and community of practice management
•	$20,000 – Adam Garry: Extended technical assistance through Phase 2 (both in-person at convenings and through regular 1:1 district team coaching)', NULL,
   'INV-089790', false, false),
  ('fd56d7f8-16c9-4f93-a898-cd0882c5ff8c', 'TX: Employment Outcomes Support Sustainability', 'Julia Bloom-Weltman', current_timestamp(),
   'Ready for Review', 'Grant', 'State and regional systems in priority contexts (TX, WA, CA) routinely produce timely and actionable insights that intermediaries and local district and higher education leaders use to drive continuous improvement in student pathways.',
   'sfl', 'sfl-bow2', NULL,
   'Ray Marshall Center', 750000, 200000,
   'Trellis, Temple (and likely other local funders)', 'Q3 (Jul-Sep)', '>2 years',
   'We provided seed funding for this project which ends in the fall. While they have been successful in fundraising, exceeding goals around matched funds, they are looking for more runway to expand their offering into years 2 and 3 to all community colleges in the state. I think there is an opportunity here to ask them to accelerate their work with AI in some big ways too- lets talk if there are partners we could pair them with and if there is appetite for this as a no regrets investment for Texas. I took a guess on amount and was thinking more for longer was best but would love your thoughts there as well.', NULL,
   'INV-085012', false, false),
  ('60a64f18-6c21-4417-916a-e4c21ee1e29b', 'TX and CA: AI Powered OBC Working Group', 'Julia Bloom-Weltman', current_timestamp(),
   'Okay to Proceed', 'Grant', 'High-readiness contexts within and across priority states implement integrated SIS–LMS–AI system-feedback-loop prototypes to
generate early evidence on effectiveness, safety, and feasibility that informs broader focus state and regional adoption.
Priority states and regions demonstrate increased human, technical, governance, and data infrastructure capacity to responsibly test,
evaluate, procure and adopt AI-enabled data solutions aligned to student needs, system goals, and guardrails for safety, privacy and
equity.​',
   'sfl', 'sfl-bow2', NULL,
   'Strategic Data Project and Center for Outcomes-Based Contracting', 1000000, 250000,
   'Pathways', 'Q3 (Jul-Sep)', '2 years',
   'Districts are not just buying software -- they are buying changes in instruction, student engagement, and learning trajectories. Without credible ways to link AI use, implementation practice, and student results, even the most promising tools risk becoming expensive pilots rather than scalable solutions. 
Working group within the two-year SDP Fellowship: 6-8 fellows per cohort from priority  districts in CA and TX who design, manage, and evaluate contracts for AI-enabled instructional tools where payment is tied to measurable learning outcomes rather than licenses or usage alone. Developed in partnership with Center for OBC. $2M over 30 months (two cohorts + cross-cohort tool development and national dissemination). 
Strong alignment with broader DAIP framing. AI-powered tools depend heavily on implementation quality but most districts lack outcome definitions that match how these tools operate or data pipelines connecting product data to student outcomes. This creates high risk for districts and weak incentives for vendors.', NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
