  ('f3c6d457-6fe7-439c-aae6-1e3305bd627d', 'Supplement Phase 0.1 of Career Village''s Career Benchmark', 'Matt Gee', current_timestamp(),
   'Brainstorming', 'Grant', 'Support PSTs (Postsecondary Success and Pathways) in expanding on career navigation specific benchmark datasets, RLHF investments on the general model behavior in advising.  Reason about how to drive towards long-term positive outcomes.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow3', 'ai-infra-bow2',
   'Career Village and Careerbench.org', 1500000, 500000,
   'Schultz', 'Q3 (Jul-Sep)', '2 years',
   'On the minds of Pavani, Maurice and Xiaoxue.  Here is a confidential note from Jared on 5/6: 

Hi everyone,

Our data team just finished a sprint that built a working next-gen career navigation benchmark proof of concept: CareerBench v0.1. They did it in just five days. Our team now has the technical means to handle all of the trickiest bits of benchmarking ops, which has convinced me that a next-level sector-wide benchmark is now within reach: CareerBench v1.0, live on careerbench.org, developed with input from 200+ AICD members, in roughly one quarter if we resource it now. I''ll include a summary of CareerBench v0.1 findings below. Please note: We are *NOT* going public with this yet. First, I''d like to understand where you all are on your benchmarking efforts, and whether moving benchmarks forward is a funding priority for anyone here. Please do let me know! 

- Jared


CareerBench v0.1 findings
Draft: Preliminary and confidential. Do not distribute or publish.

Topline: The benchmark works. We can detect meaningful quality differences across model generations, model families, model versions, career nav use cases, and — most importantly for our mission — across user demographic characteristics. We can also quantify how much application-layer services improve on top of base models, including Coach versus its underlying foundation models, and competing services against each other.
•	Benchmark structure insights: Our team was able to validate that the majority of career nav use case chats can be eval''ed using a high-dimensional binary (pass/fail) eval space using both human-as-a-judge and LLM-as-a-judge. CareerBench v0.1 validated this using 26 evals sampled from our library of 200+ evals, but it''s clear to us that a full CareerBench v1.0 would require many hundreds or thousands of binary pass/fail evals provided by a diverse array of subject-matter-experts (not just our staff). We are also testing controlled pairwise comparison evals, to test for bias, but expect that to come in a future edition of CareerBench (v2.0 or later). Conversations can be both human-generated and synthetic-data-generated, and the v1.0 dataset will likely have to have a combination of both with validity checks on the synthetic dataset.
•	Technical capability insights: Given the large scale of the analysis, and the large number of experiment parameters, our team had to build a fair bit of custom tooling. The core primitives were already elements of our internal quality-checking systems, but for it all to work in a benchmarking context, they had to customize things quite a bit. We''ve now built up almost all of the technical infra needed to do this kind of work at larger scale: human and synthetic conversation generation, data versioning, annotation, the scaled evals platform, and the analysis tools.
•	Workplan and resource insights: This sprint pulled 7 team members for 5 days, which cost us a sizeable amount in personnel costs, plus about $20K in nominal token costs (although thankfully most of those were free credits donated by the major labs). This sprint reaffirmed that effective benchmark development for career nav will require: (1) a significant amount of iteration on testing parameters to find a stable set of evaluation conditions (the performance results moved a lot throughout this project as we iteratively dialed in our test parameters), (2) a very large dataset (both human and validated synthetic) that covers a surprisingly broad use case space and a large space of user demographic characteristics, (3) early engagement with the major labs, (4) a large bevy of subject-matter-experts to annotate data (we propose AICD) across a huge space of likely many-hundreds-to-a-few-thousand quality criteria, (5) a very healthy token budget, (6) a process quarterback (CIP or similar), and (7) a technical lead for the project (CV data team or similar).
We''re deliberately not naming individual model winners and losers from v0.1. The validity of those claims depends on the multi-stakeholder process (SMEs defining quality criteria and annotating) that v1.0 is designed to be. Publishing rankings before that work is done could undercut benchmark credibility. That said, we''re happy to show anonymized findings in confidence, to demonstrate the capabilities we have developed.', NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
