   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow2', 'ai-infra-bow3',
   'Humane-Intelligence Public Benefit Corporation and Learning Tapestry', 125000, 125000,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '<1 year',
   NULL, NULL,
   'INV-106676', true, false),
  ('08e72242-e7b2-4fc4-a3d4-6f0cec3e6e95', 'cognitive harm & cognitive flourishing framework for AI-enabled tutoring', 'Pavani Reddy', current_timestamp(),
   'Ready for Review', 'Grant', 'Evaluation infrastructure for AI tutoring harms — specifically for K12 and college students in under-resourced contexts. A quick summary is to develop a taxonomy of overreliance of tutoring-related harms (cognitive offloading, over-scaffolding, identity-contingent quality degradation, stereotype reinforcement, etc.) with observable indicators and instrument design specs.  The effort then proceeds to build a harms-aware evaluation bench by extending a third-party corpus (NTO) with a scoring rubric and construct-based scenarios, producing a benchmark report on frontier model performance, create a gold standard reference set by running derived scenarios through external evaluators and comparing their judgments against hidden ground-truth labels — effectively validating evaluation methods themselves and make the harm-annotated corpus publicly available via open licensing.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow2', 'ai-infra-bow2',
   'Virginia State University FRAME anchored at Virginia State University''s Center for Responsible AI, as a subgrant from Humane-Intelligence PBC', 2510000, 1500000,
   'should view this in relationship with NTO supplement concept which I entered on Matt''s behalf since Bryan would appreciate a thought partner', 'Q3 (Jul-Sep)', '>2 years',
   'There is an interest and push - which I have included - from Nancy Otero Ornelas - to open source the test harness produced in NTO so that AI researchers can leverage it more easily.', NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
  ('610d833f-e1cf-4c9d-9c52-6e69ca0b1a66', 'Co-investment to INV-101277 - AI Infrastructure and Feature Testing', 'Pavani Reddy', current_timestamp(),
   'Okay to Proceed', 'Grant', 'A co-investment directly to The Emancipation Group (TEG) in the range of $310,000–$420,000 could allow for ongoing sustainability for TEG’s work here. Depending on what the partners agree, it might fund some combination of:
•	Integration of TEG’s bias taxonomy, adversarial probe protocol, and scoring rubric into Humane-Intelligence Public Benefit Corporation’s evaluation platform as hosted, runnable modules, with HIPBC engaged as a technical subcontractor to TEG
•	Development of a TEG-branded certification protocol and mark that gives districts a procurement-ready signal without requiring internal machine learning expertise
•	A post-grant operational bridge that establishes TEG’s revenue streams — certification fees, knowledge base maintenance subscriptions, and commissioned taxonomy extensions — before the primary grant closes',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow2', NULL,
   'The Emancipation Group', 420000, 200000,
   'Titilola Harley is the primary IO', 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '2 years',
   NULL, NULL,
   'INV-101277', false, false),
  ('52ccd316-6df2-4566-8075-bc3f03d3dbee', 'Learning Context as a foundational construct for interoperable, context-aware learning systems', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Moved to Invest', 'Grant', '1EdTech proposes a Request for Comment (RFC) process focused on defining Learning Context as a foundational construct for interoperable, context-aware learning systems.
The RFC will establish architectural principles for:
- Defining learning context: what constitutes learning context, how it is structured, and how required versus optional elements are expressed.
- Policy enablement: how permissions to access, share, or withhold elements of learning context are granted or denied through machine- and human-readable policy.
- Coordination and orchestration: how learning context is compiled, assembled, and maintained at scale across multiple systems of record, agents, and services.
The RFC will specify the pattern, not the implementation. We will not commit to specific query languages, policy formats, or credential schemas. The goal is alignment on principles—request, policy, receipt operating at the level of context—that can inform future standards work without prematurely foreclosing technical choices.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow1', NULL,
   '1EdTech', 98500, 98500,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '1 year',
   NULL, NULL,
   'INV-103756', true, false),
  ('a517e453-d8be-47d8-ab1a-33f3b75b9088', 'The Privacy Valuation Project: Valuing What We Cant Afford to ignore', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Okay to Proceed', 'Grant', 'The central question for all technology use should be simple: does this move us closer to the kind of society we want to live in or further from it? But the logic of tech development & adoption often defaults to the logic of inevitability. 
● Often, new technologies & uses are seen as inevitable, instead of as things we can actively shape. We should start with the problem and design efficacious solutions, but frequently build the tech and then try to find applications for it (e.g. GenAI and LLMs).
● In order to enable this, we need to account for the values we fail to measure—privacy, dignity, trust, autonomy, fairness.
● The result: rapid technological acceleration with uncertain social consequences.
We need tools that make those invisible costs and benefits legible so that public interest values can influence tech development & adoptions, rather than just reacting after the fact. 

We value what we count—and we count what we value.

The most enduring policy tools— like the Social Cost of Carbon—made once-abstract harms and benefits of specific actions measurable. They made trade-offs visible, grounded regulation in evidence, and turned principles into enforceable standards.
This project would form a coalition to build off of that model to do the same for tech benefits and harms → a structured scalable valuation framework for data-driven emerging technologies like AI, as well as privacy and data use.',
   'ai-infra', NULL, NULL,
   NULL, NULL, NULL,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', NULL,
   NULL, NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
  ('d61676dd-0eb9-497c-a40f-bdceceb25567', 'Open Source PET User Testing and GRAND REPORT', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Moved to Invest', NULL, 'MDI will conduct the testing and comparing of popular, primarily open-source PET tools using realistic in-house simulated datasets, chosen based on SLDS input. The Guides for Common PETs Tools will initially focus on synthetic data, secure hashing, and secure enclaves, rooted in preferences recorded from discussions with more than 20 states to date. We will begin by testing three (3) major open-source synthetic data tools, and three (3) major open-source secure hashing tools. For each PET and its 3 tools, we will categorize them by key implementation elements specific to SLDS’s, such as data preparation needs, data quality pitfalls, and infrastructure requirements. Results will be written up into publicly available materials. Rachel''s pushing for a grand annual report. 

But why does the field need this?
There is currently no overarching guidance across the myriad PET options that SLDS’s and their affiliated support organizations face. We are motivated to create these PET guides because:
●	They can answer current questions we receive from SLDS’s. Over the last few years, we have heard common themes across SLDS staff’s PET questions, about the PET tools themselves and how to choose the best fit for their organization: 
○	Should I buy an enclave, build one myself, or use a third party?  
○	Do you know if [Cloud Service Provider’s] clean room is good enough to meet my needs? 
○	Which synthetic data statistical method is best? 
○	Is my current hashing method secure? 
○	Which hashing tools are best suited to the needs of SLDS data, with fuzzy linkage requirements and no unique identifiers? 
●	They will save the SLDS’s time, a limited resource in many government teams. 
●	They push SLDS’s in safer directions, by bringing the privacy expertise to them. 
●	They connect to other SLDS community efforts.  
●	They can be built upon by the community.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow1', NULL,
   'Georgetown MDI', 1000000, 300000,
   'Possible co-funding opp with Julia/DAIP', 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '2 years',
   NULL, NULL,
   'INV-105238', true, false),
  ('104a3195-7e5a-44d4-9837-076a8809e081', 'Catalyzing AI in Higher Ed', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Brainstorming', 'Grant', 'By building shared, evidence-driven, and learner-centered AI infrastructure, this initiative positions the sector to responsibly harness AI at scale in order to expand opportunity, strengthen trust, and transform how learning is personalized, governed, and delivered for millions of students. ASU is uniquely positioned with the capacity, expertise and scale to meet this decisive moment facing higher education.
•	•  
Institute for Use-Inspired AI Research: Establish a rigorous, rapid-cycle research and evaluation hub that builds sector-wide trust in AI by producing transparent evidence on efficacy, ethics, bias, and learning impact—accelerating responsible adoption through open, credible scholarship. 
•	•  
AI Platform and Service Lab (Digital Public Infrastructure): Democratize access to high-quality AI in higher education through a shared, low-cost, multi-tenant platform that enables resource-constrained institutions to deploy, govern, and improve AI tools at scale while preserving autonomy and trust. 
•	•  
Semantic Learning Memory Experimentation: Advance privacy-preserving, learner-owned AI memory systems to support truly personalized, longitudinal learning—grounded in learning science and early experimentation to inform future standards, interoperability, and learner agency.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow1', NULL,
   'ASU', NULL, NULL,
   NULL, NULL, NULL,
   'Detail is linked here: https://bmgf.sharepoint.com/:w:/r/sites/USProgramDataTeam/Shared%20Documents/AI%20Infrastructure/Concepts/ASU_Catalyzing%20AI%20in%20Higher%20Ed%20-%20Jan%20Draft.docx?d=w0bc04bfec2d54aab9fdca642133d171f&csf=1&web=1&e=hrZPuc', NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
  ('b9d102f5-f09a-445f-a397-8aea6fd03532', 'Operationalizing CEDS Innovation, Forging AI-Powered Community', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Moved to Invest', 'Grant', 'Challenge Statement. The education to workforce data ecosystem is at an inflection point. Increased adoption of standards and the immense potential of AI has created the potential for a once in a generation opportunity. Despite a decade of foundational investment in standards, data systems, and cross sector collaboration, the field’s ability to absorb, align, and implement these innovations has not kept pace. Today, the challenge is not a lack of innovation, but a growing gap between what is possible and what can be operationalized. 
Why AEM? For over a decade, we have operated at the intersection of innovation and practice. Priority investments and initiatives regularly seek our expertise, with an average of 15+ outreach requests per month for ad hoc support related to standards, privacy, and stakeholder engagement. We also maintain deep connections across all 50+ state education systems.
What is the Ask?  Fund AEM to serve as a field-level coordinating and enabling backbone that connects state demand, priority investments, and emerging standards infrastructure to accelerate adoption and reduce fragmentation at a critical inflection point.
Through two integrated scopes of work, AEM will:
•	Activate and align state demand by generating real-time intelligence, engaging states in structured cohorts, and convening multi-state efforts that validate, refine, and accelerate priority investments. 
•	Advance a coherent, AI-ready standards ecosystem by coordinating across standards efforts, embedding technical expertise into investments, and operationalizing shared semantic infrastructure (CEDS and ontology) and governance models that enable scalable, interoperable, open-source AI ready solutions. 
This work ensures that innovation across the ecosystem is not only developed—but aligned, adopted, and operationalized at scale—unlocking the full value of prior investments and enabling a more coherent, AI-ready education-to-workforce data ecosystem',
   'ai-infra', 'hub-bow1', NULL,
   'AEM', NULL, NULL,
   'SFL Portfolio?', 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '>2 years',
   NULL, NULL,
   'INV-106121', true, false),
  ('dc267804-4b84-4cea-89fc-2ffda550ee18', 'LIF Initiative Alignment & AI Enablement', 'Rachel Scherer', current_timestamp(),
   'Brainstorming', 'Contract', 'The Learner Information Framework (LIF) is emerging as a shared interoperability layer across a growing set of initiatives focused on improving learner data portability, usability, and cross-sector integration. As efforts such as Digital Holistic Student Supports (DHSS), EduCore, AACRAO Infuse, and the New Data Paradigm advance, there is increasing alignment around the need for common infrastructure to translate, compose, and operationalize learner data across systems. At the same time, the rapid evolution of AI tools and agent-based workflows is introducing new requirements for how data must be structured, accessed, and maintained.
This proposal outlines an investment to advance LIF as AI-ready public infrastructure by strengthening its core components, integrating partner contributions, aligning to USP-priority initiatives, and supporting ecosystem adoption. The work will focus on enabling developers and AI tools to effectively use LIF, supporting real-world implementations, and building on early field-building efforts to accelerate the transition from awareness to active adoption.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow1', 'hub-bow1;sfl-bow2;sfl-bow1',
   'Unicon', 1700000, 765000,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '2 years',
   NULL, NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
