  ('e94393ae-1c00-4a54-be04-3155d519b3fd', 'Digital Promise: 9th Grade on Track Google Expansion', 'Vic Vuchic', current_timestamp(),
   'Ready for Review', 'Supplement to existing INV', 'Student success teams rely on a myriad of data to proactively identify students at-risk of falling off-track, connect them to appropriate interventions, and monitor their progress to ensure their needs are met to achieve on-time graduation. However, teams often struggle to wade through the data to discern actionable takeaways and strategies. This challenge stems from two major issues in the 9th Grade On Track (9GOT) technical ecosystem: (1) data are disconnected and scattered across discrete systems and (2) patterns are difficult to identify with so many variables to consider. 

 AI’s value in supporting student success initiatives is clear: compressing the time between diagnosis and intervention assignment. AI addresses the very pain points teams experience as it can pull scattered, nuanced signals into clear insights that help student success teams understand why a student is off track and offer research-based intervention strategies that meet those identified needs. The manual labor reduction enables student success teams to spend less time hunting for information and more time strengthening relationships with students and families to collaboratively determine a path forward. 

This hypothesis drove the first phase of Digital Promise’s work in 9GOT: partnering with providers like Panorama, Innovare, and PowerSchool, to co-design AI-enabled features that address user needs. Based on early cohort learnings, the demand from student success teams is not just for accessible data, but for features that smooth the decision moments. Through co-design sessions, product teams focused on ways to leverage AI for efforts like early signals detection and abbreviating the time between diagnosis and intervention assignment. Early usage data from co-design partners indicates greater uptake of the tools from co-design school and district partners. These early findings indicate that improving existing tools can support teams with reviewing and interpreting data, streamlining internal workflows, and assigning interventions. 

If this first co-design cohort is showing us that AI compresses diagnosis-to-assignment time, we believe Google integration could help student success teams ensure that assignment turns into execution and tracking—by pushing outputs directly into the tools teams already use to run the work. This critical part of the configuration puzzle requires partnership with a primary tool many teams leverage in their existing workflows. Our District-Led Innovations Showcase demonstrates that Google Suite is a primary platform for many stages of this work, including intervention executing and monitoring, capturing notes, and managing follow-ups. There are many knowledgeable Google Suite users who have stitched together a streamlined workflow. Google has a track record for acquiring best-in-class technology to enrich its own offerings (see Brightbytes) and already integrates with many student information systems. Moreover, Google tends to offer their tools for free to users, addressing a consistent market problem with other tools where the best features come with the highest premiums. Through co-design with experts on school and district teams as well as subject matter experts, like GRAD Partnership, NCS, and CORE, we can translate research to practice in designing flexible Google tools that respond to real technological gaps experienced by users. By leveraging Google''s support of implementation workflows we can use AI to tighten the feedback loops from identifying interventions to implementing them to capturing results.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow3', NULL,
   'Digital Promise', 200000, 75000,
   '~100000 from Assessment team', 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '1 year',
   'This grant would have a 2 phase approach.  Phase 1 (~$125k) would be co-design with Google and the districts to determine a viable configuration and toolkit that Google could implement.  Phase 2 (~$175k) would be development and piloting of the design.  Phase 2 would be contingent on a successful concept emerging from Phase 1 with Google''s buy-in.', NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
