  ('5d605e81-66fc-4b92-8341-b3a9a728face', 'Hack club planning grant', 'Xiaoxue Du', current_timestamp(),
   'Brainstorming', 'Grant', 'Hack Club × MVC: Vision, Costs, and Next Steps
The vision
By 2030, 1 million teenagers will have shipped real, open-source projects through Hack Club and the Minimal Viable Coalition — the by-kids-for-kids ecosystem Xiaoxue and Matt described in the MVC framing. Teen-led AI labs, safe sandbox environments, open-source tooling, identity and trust infrastructure, and the shared starter kits and playbooks that let any teen anywhere participate.
Hack Club already runs the engine at 100,000 teens (22,776 projects shipped in 2025, up 4.3x from 2024). The coalition could unlock the path to 1M. Hack Club''s total cost over five years is: $100M at a cost rate of less than $10/hour of teen building, making Hack Club the most effective and cost-efficient STEM programs in the US. This is the infrastructure for a true STEM pipeline: technical skills, applied math, individual agency and entrepreneurship and healthy peer-to-peer relationships. 
Why now
AI has lowered the floor for what a 14-year-old can build, but nothing in the existing youth ecosystem is built for "by kids, for kids." Most platforms are curriculum-led, adult-designed, and closed. The next 18 months will set the pattern for whether teens enter the AI era as builders or as consumers. Gates Foundation''s role as a convener of public-good infrastructure is what makes the difference between Hack Club continuing to grow steadily on its own (reaching maybe 300K teens by 2030) versus a true coalition movement reaching 1M.
What Hack Club brings
Hack Club already reached 100,000 teen builders in 2025. 50,000 in our Slack with 1M+ messages/month. 700 teenagers applied to work at Hack Club in our 1-year Gap Year and 47 were selected, meaning Hack Club has 80% teen engineering staff plus 500 teen volunteers. We employ an ID verification system already trusted by Microsoft''s GitHub. Hack Club hosts sandbox environments where a 14-year-old can fork and build a working AI app in 10 minutes. 10,000 teens attended in-person hackathons in 2025 (up from 53 in 2021)- and we project 25k students in attendance in 2026. Grant-to-prize efficiency of $12 per hour of teen building.
Funding: Lightening Grant and Big Picture
We''ve designed three tiers so Gates and other coalition partners can engage at whatever level fits.
Tier 1 — Lightning grant (next 30–60 days). A menu of three modular deliverables, each producing visible open-source public goods by end of 2026: 
(A) the July 21–22 MVC launch moment in SF, $250K; exact conference schedule is TBD by next week. 
(B) Coalition infrastructure v1 — open-source sandbox tooling, identity/trust playbook, starter kits, implementation playbook, $400K; 
(C) A documented six-month Teen AI Builder Lab cohort of 50 teens in person convening for discussions with Gates team and with case studies for Gates internal use, $350K. 
(D) "Gates Foundation Gap Years" directly funds 10 teen engineers'' 1-year Gap Years and has a direct connection with the Foundation: $1m
These are suggested Gates Foundation could fund one, two, or all four. Suggested combinations: minimum $250K with maximum $2M.
Big picture: Hack Club''s 5 year plan to build a STEM Pipeline for teenagers built by and for them
Tier 2 — Year 1 anchor commitment (12 months). Hack Club''s full annual operating cost is $20M, across the teen-led AI Education Lab, prizes and hardware, hackathons, coalition infrastructure, ops, and storytelling. The portion most aligned with Gates''s stated MVC priorities — sandbox tooling, identity/trust, starter kits, playbooks, and the teen-led lab — totals roughly $9M annually. We''d suggest framing the Year 1 conversation around that envelope, alongside frontier AI partners (AMD at $1M, others in conversation at $1M+) and other philanthropic partners.
Tier 3 — Five-year coalition vision: $100M. Year 1: 100K teens, $20M cumulative. Year 3: 450K teens, $65M cumulative. Year 5: 1M teens, $100M cumulative. All-in cost per shipped project drops from $200 to $100 over the period. Transparent unit economics where every dollar maps to a shipped project.
Hack Club can provide a more detailed proposal for these options. 
Coalition structure
Per Xiaoxue''s framing, three groups: philanthropic partners (Gates, plus suggested Ballmer, Stand Together/Koch, Overdeck, Siegel, Schultz, and 1–2 others for discussion), frontier AI companies (AMD already committed; Anthropic, OpenAI, Microsoft, Google, Meta, xAI in conversation at $1M+ each for the "advanced AI pack for every teen builder" tier), and ecosystem collaborators already. working with Hack Club (US Congressional App Challenge, CSTA, MIT BeaverWorks Program; Code.org, Vercel Education, GitHub Education, plus a consortium of rural and regional partners).  
Suggested next steps
This week: names added to MVC doc, AMD July 23 details sent to Matt. Within two weeks: working session with Melanie to scope lightning grant and Year 1. Late June: Burlington visit if useful. July 21–22: MVC convening + SF hackathon. July 23: AMD stage with two-track Gates participation language (fuller or lighter-touch). August–December: lightning grant deliverables shipped. Q4 2026: Year 1 anchor commitment finalized.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow3', NULL,
   'Hack Club', NULL, NULL,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', NULL,
   NULL, NULL,
   NULL, false, false),
  ('e631b975-c943-42f5-9ac8-be9f93d2fc83', 'Stanford Memory Planning Grant', 'Xiaoxue Du', current_timestamp(),
   'Moved to Invest', 'Grant', 'To define a Memory Global Stack as a shared, modular infrastructure that enables AI systems to scale responsibly across sectors - serving as a global public good for education, workforce, and public systems. The ambition is to move from fragmented, pilot-driven adoption toward a coherent, interoperable system where core layers (data, identity, models/agents, evaluation, interoperability) are reusable and aligned across contexts. Leverage Stanford HAI for a planning effort to define the Memory Global Stack architecture as a foundation for public-good infrastructure. The focus would be on technical system design to ensure the stack is modular and extensible across global use cases.',
   'ai-infra', 'ai-infra-bow1', NULL,
   'Stanford Digital Economy Lab', 250000, NULL,
   NULL, 'Q2 (Apr-Jun)', '<1 year',
   'To define a Memory Global Stack as a shared, modular infrastructure that enables AI systems to scale responsibly across sectors - serving as a global public good for education, workforce, and public systems. The ambition is to move from fragmented, pilot-driven adoption toward a coherent, interoperable system where core layers (data, identity, models/agents, evaluation, interoperability) are reusable and aligned across contexts. Leverage Stanford HAI for a planning effort to define the Memory Global Stack architecture as a foundation for public-good infrastructure. The focus would be on technical system design to ensure the stack is modular and extensible across global use cases.

Sizing: ~250k with 10% overhead 

Phrase 1. Scope (8–12 weeks)
1. Visioning & Stack Definition
•	Define the Memory stack layers (data, identity, model/agent, evaluation, interoperability) 
•	Clarify system boundaries, interfaces, and guiding principles 
•	Align with emerging global memory infrastructure efforts 
2. Architecture & System Design
•	Develop end-to-end system architecture (components, data flows, interfaces) 
•	Specify requirements for modularity, observability, extensibility, and interoperability 
•	Position evaluation and feedback loops as core infrastructure 
3. Ecosystem & Gap Analysis
•	Map existing global efforts (DPI, AI infra, standards) 
•	Identify critical gaps and opportunities for public-good investment 
4. Governance & Design Principles
•	Define principles for privacy, user control, auditability, and safety 
•	Outline governance considerations for shared infrastructure 
5. Roadmap to Prototype (Phase 2), Piloting and Scaling 
•	Define a phased pathway (architecture → prototype → pilot → scale) 
•	Identify technical dependencies and potential partners

Deliverables 
This planning effort sets up a clear pathway to Phase 2 (prototyping with domain partners) and Phase 3/4 (scaling and contributing reusable components as global public goods).
•	Personal Context Router Stack blueprint (architecture, layers, interfaces) 
•	Design principles for open, interoperable infrastructure 
•	Identity 1-2 design patters 
•	Position paper/concepts for memory stack 
•	6–12-month roadmap toward prototyping and partnerships

This effort shifts the field from application-level innovation to infrastructure-first design, creating a shared foundation for AI systems. By defining the AI Memory Global Stack as a global public good, it enables interoperability across systems, scalable and responsible deployment, more equitable access to AI capabilities, and faster innovation through reusable infrastructure.', NULL,
   'INV-101035', true, false);

